DOCUMENT();

loadMacros(
  "PGstandard.pl",
  "MathObjects.pl",
  "PGML.pl",
  "contextFraction.pl",
  "contextLimitedRadical.pl",
  "PGcourse.pl",
  "parserRoot.pl",
);

######################################

TEXT(beginproblem());
Context("Numeric");
Context()->variables->add(p =>'Real', q =>'Real', r =>'Real'); 

#square root
$n1 = random(2, 10);
$a1 = random(1, 8);
$m1 = $n1 + 2*$a1;
$p1 = 2*$a1;
$rad1 = Formula("p^$m1/p^$n1");

#cube root
$n2 = random(2, 10);
$a2 = random(1, 8);
$m2 = $n2 + 3*$a2;
$p2 = 3*$a2;
$rad2 = Formula("q^$m2/q^$n2");

#4th root
$n3 = random(2, 10);
$a3 = random(1, 8);
$m3 = $n3 + 4*$a3;
$p3 = 4*$a3;
$rad3 = Formula("r^$m3/r^$n3");

Context("LimitedRadical");
Context()->variables->add(p =>'Real', q =>'Real', r =>'Real'); 

$ans1 = Formula("p^$a1");
$ans2 = Formula("q^$a2");
$ans3 = Formula("r^$a3");


##########################################


#####################################################

BEGIN_PGML

Simplify each radical. Assume all variables are positive.

Use *root(n, x)* to enter [`\sqrt[n]{x}`]. For example: [`\sqrt[3]{2} =`]  *root(3, 2)* and [`\sqrt[4]{y^{3}} = `] *root(4, y^3)*.

  (a)  [`` \sqrt{[$rad1]} = ``] [_____________]{$ans1}
  (b)  [`` \sqrt[3]{[$rad2]} = ``] [_____________]{$ans2}
  (c)  [`` \sqrt[4]{[$rad3]} = ``] [_____________]{$ans3}
END_PGML

############################################################


BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION
In each of these exercises: reduce first, then simplify.  We can simplify by subtracting the exponents.

  (a)  [`` \sqrt{[$rad1]} = \sqrt{p^{[$p1]}} = [$ans1]``]
  
  (b)  [`` \sqrt[3]{[$rad2]} = \sqrt[3]{q^{[$p2]}} = [$ans2]``]
  
  (c)  [`` \sqrt[4]{[$rad3]} = \sqrt[4]{r^{[$p3]}} = [$ans3]``]

END_PGML_SOLUTION

######################################



ENDDOCUMENT();
